The data includes a binary variable for whether or not the country has a program, economic variables, geopolitical variables etc. The data set originally came from here, though the Rdata version of it was produced by me. The data set was used in the following paper:

Jo, Dong-Joon, and Erik Gartzke. 2007. Determinants of Nuclear Weapons Proliferation: A Quantitative Model. The Journal of Conflict Resolution 51(1):167-194.

Logistic Regression: Predicting a Binary Outcome

In this lecture we will be interested in predicting whether a nation has a nuclear weapons program in a given year. This variable will be 0 or 1, so we would like our regression model to give a prediction in this range so that we can interpret the output as a probability. Unfortunately, a standard linear regression model can give an output of any real number. Therefore, we would like a model that has its output restricted to the range 0 to 1. To do this we will construct a model that predicts a real number and then map that number to the range 0 to 1. Specifically, the model will have the form

=0+1x1+2x2+nxn.=0+1x1+2x2+nxn.
Then this output will be mapped to the range [0,1][0,1] using the inverse logit function. The logit function is given by
logit(p)=log(p1p).logit(p)=log(p1p).
 Therefore, we can find the value of the probability as a function of the xx variables by using the inverse of the logit function
p(x)=logit1()=ee+1.p(x)=logit1()=ee+1.
 Often, is called the logarithm of the odds, or more commonly log odds. This is because the odds of an outcome are given by the fraction p/(1p)p/(1p), that is the ratio of the probability of success to the probability failure.

We call such a model a logit model because we are predicting the logit of the probability. The estimation of the coefficients ii is done differently than for a standard linear model. For a description of how this is done, see this lecture. The basic idea is that we consider the outcome is a binomial random variable with probability of success given by p=logit1()p=logit1(). By maximizing the binomial likelihood over the parameters ii, one fits the model.

Our first logit model

We want to see if the likelihood of having a nuclear weapons program in a given year is likely based on whether a state had a program in the previous year. We can look at this using a probability table.

with(nw,table(nuk_apl,nuk_a_p))
##        nuk_a_p
## nuk_apl    0    1
##       0 5826   13
##       1   24  464

This is a bit ugly, so lets rename the variables

nw_rename <- rename(nw, NW.Program = nuk_a_p, NW.Program.Prev.Year = nuk_apl)
with(nw_rename,table(NW.Program.Prev.Year,NW.Program))
##                     NW.Program
## NW.Program.Prev.Year    0    1
##                    0 5826   13
##                    1   24  464

We can now make a model that attempts to predict whether a state will have a NW program in a given year based solely on whether it had one in the previous year:

summary(simp.model <- glm(NW.Program ~ NW.Program.Prev.Year, data = nw_rename, family = binomial(link = "logit")))

From this result we can see that the presence of program in the previous year is a significant predictor based on the significance of the coefficient.

I will define an inverse logit function for convenience

invlogit <- function(x) exp(x)/(1+exp(x))

Lets look at the probability of developing a nuclear weapons program for a country that does not have a program. In this example this quantity is related to the intercept because the value of NW.Program.Prev.Year is zero for a country that did not have a program in the previous year:

log(p1p)=6.1051366log(p1p)=6.1051366
p1p=exp(6.1051366)=0.0022314p1p=exp(6.1051366)=0.0022314
p=logit1(6.1051366)=0.0022264p=logit1(6.1051366)=0.0022264
 This means that there is a 0.22% chance of a state that did not have a NW program the year before developing a program.

We could also look at the probability that a country that has a program the previous year keeping it:

log(p1p)=6.1051366+9.0669673=2.9618307log(p1p)=6.1051366+9.0669673=2.9618307
p1p=exp(2.9618307)=19.3333333p1p=exp(2.9618307)=19.3333333
p=logit1(2.9618307)=0.9508197p=logit1(2.9618307)=0.9508197

More Complicated Models

Based on these results, having a rival with nuclear weapons increases the log odds of having a nuclear weapons program by 1.5390772. We can see how much more likely a country without a program is to develop a program if it has a rival with a program. Based on this model the probability of a country with a rival NW program developing NWs in a given year is

log(pnorival1pnorival)=6.2400569log(pnorival1pnorival)=6.2400569
pnorival1pnorival=exp(6.2400569)=0.0019497pnorival1pnorival=exp(6.2400569)=0.0019497
pnorival=logit1(6.2400569)=0.001946pnorival=logit1(6.2400569)=0.001946

If the country HAS a rival with a NW program then the probability is

log(prival1prival)=6.2400569+1.5390772=4.7009797log(prival1prival)=6.2400569+1.5390772=4.7009797
prival1prival=exp(4.7009797)=0.0090864prival1prival=exp(4.7009797)=0.0090864
prival=logit1(4.7009797)=0.0090046prival=logit1(4.7009797)=0.0090046

Therefore, the increase in the probability is privalpnorival=0.0070586privalpnorival=0.0070586.

For the next model we will add a continuous variable: the logarithm of the number of years since 1938.

nw_rename <- mutate(nw_rename, Year = as.integer(exp(l_year_t) + 1938))

This model tells us that as time has marched on, the likelihood of a state developing nuclear weapons increases. When we use a continuous variable in a logistic model, it can be useful to plot the effect of the variable in a chart of the following form.

pred_vals <- data_frame(Year = rep(seq(1940,1993),4), 
                        Rival.NW = c(rep(0,(1994-1940)*2),rep(1,(1994-1940)*2)),
                        NW.Program.Prev.Year = c(rep(0,(1994-1940)),rep(1,(1994-1940)),
                                                 rep(1,(1994-1940)),rep(0,(1994-1940))))
pred_vals <- mutate(pred_vals, l_year_t = log(Year-1938))
pred_vals <- mutate(pred_vals,NW.Program = predict(model3, pred_vals, type='response'))
ggplot(nw_rename, aes(x = Year, y = NW.Program, color = as.factor(Rival.NW), shape = as.factor(NW.Program.Prev.Year))) + geom_jitter(width = 0.99, height = 0.1,alpha = 0.75) + geom_line(data=pred_vals, aes(linetype = as.factor(NW.Program.Prev.Year)), size = 1.25) + scale_color_manual("Rival is NW State", values = c("0" = "blue", "1"="green") ) + scale_shape_discrete("Program Prev Year") + scale_linetype_discrete("Program Prev Year")  + theme_bw() + scale_y_continuous("Probability of Developing NW Program")

Notice that the impact of year is nonlinear: it has an larger impact early on than later. This is due to both the logarithmic transform of the the year and the logistic map.

Something we would want to test is the false positive and false negative rates for our model. Ideally, we would do this using an in and out of sample test. That is, we would build the model on some fraction of the data and test it on the other portion. We will do this later, but first we will use all the data to build and test the model. As we will see it is important to set the threshold for the prediction to say that country will develop a program in a given year. The simplest threshold would be 50% so that the model says the country is more likely than not to develop a program. We could increase that threshold to be more conservative so that we only say a country will develop a program when the model is more certain. One the other hand, we could lower the threshold if we want to identify countries that are potentially likely to develop a program. There will be tradeoffs in these approaches as we will see.

nw_predict <- mutate(nw_rename, Pred = predict(model3, nw_rename, type = "response"))
yes_no <- function(x,level) 1*(x>level) 
nw_predict <- mutate(nw_predict, Level50 = yes_no(Pred,0.5))
level50 <- group_by(nw_predict, Level50, NW.Program) %>% summarise(number=n())
print(level50)
## Source: local data frame [4 x 3]
## Groups: Level50 [?]
## 
##   Level50 NW.Program number
##     (dbl)      (int)  (int)
## 1       0          0   5826
## 2       0          1     13
## 3       1          0     24
## 4       1          1    464

When we use 50% as the threshold we have a false positive rate (that is how often we say that a state will have a program when actually it didnt) of

24464+24=0.049180324464+24=0.0491803

The false negative rate is the fraction of times where the model says a country will not have a program when it does develop one. This number is

1313+5826=0.00222641313+5826=0.0022264

To decrease the false positive rate we could increase the threshold from 50% to, for example, 90%. Here are the results for making this change:

nw_predict <- mutate(nw_predict, Level90 = yes_no(Pred,0.9))
level90 <- group_by(nw_predict, Level90, NW.Program) %>% summarise(number=n())
print(level90)
## Source: local data frame [4 x 3]
## Groups: Level90 [?]
## 
##   Level90 NW.Program number
##     (dbl)      (int)  (int)
## 1       0          0   5834
## 2       0          1     55
## 3       1          0     16
## 4       1          1    422

This makes the false positive rate drop to 0.0365297 based on the calculation:

16422+16=0.036529716422+16=0.0365297

The flip-side is, however, that the false negative rate goes up to 0.0093394 based on the calculation:

5555+5834=0.00933945555+5834=0.0093394

Finally, if we lower our threshold we effectively say that we are sensitive to a nation developing a program, we will increase our false positive rate and drop our false negative rate. If we set the threshold to 1.5% (that is, if there is a 1.5% chance of a country developing a program in a given year we call that a yes), the false positive rate should jump.

nw_predict <- mutate(nw_predict, Level15 = yes_no(Pred,0.015))
level15 <- group_by(nw_predict, Level15, NW.Program) %>% summarise(number=n())
print(level15)
## Source: local data frame [4 x 3]
## Groups: Level15 [?]
## 
##   Level15 NW.Program number
##     (dbl)      (int)  (int)
## 1       0          0   5816
## 2       0          1     13
## 3       1          0     34
## 4       1          1    464

This makes the false positive rate increase to 0.0682731 based on the calculation:

34464+34=0.068273134464+34=0.0682731

Now the false negative rate goes down to 0.0022302 based on the calculation:

1313+5816=0.00223021313+5816=0.0022302

With a classification model the upshot is that the user has to specify which is worse a false positive or a false negative, and adjust the use of the model accordingly.

Predicting Development of a Program

One way to use such a model would be to predict if a country will develop a program in the next year. You could use this data to try and head off such a program (or I suppose to have a pre-emptive strike). To show how well this model would do we will make a prediction for year nn using only the data up through year n1n1. To do this we also will not try to predict any countries abandoning a program, only countries that develop one.

First, lets define an R function that predicts the number of new NW states in a given year given previous years of data.

predict_year = function(dta, year_consider, threshold = 0.5){
  build_dta <- filter(dta, Year < year_consider, NW.Program.Prev.Year == 0)
  test_dta <- filter(dta, Year==year_consider, NW.Program.Prev.Year == 0)
  result= c(0,sum(test_dta$NW.Program))
  if (nrow(test_dta) > 0) {
  year_model <- glm(NW.Program ~ Rival.NW  + majpow + nuk7set1 + l_year_t, data = build_dta, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
  preds <- predict(year_model, test_dta, type = "response")
  result[[1]] = sum( 1.0*(preds > threshold))
  }
  result
}
results <- data_frame(year = seq(1941,1993))
results <- mutate(results, Predicted.New.Prog = -1, Actual.New.Prog = 0)
count = 1
for (i in results$year) {
  results[count,2:3] <- predict_year(nw_rename, i, 0.03)
  count <- count + 1
}
meltDF <- melt(results, id="year")
ggplot(meltDF, aes(x=year, y = as.factor(value), shape = variable)) + geom_point(size = 4, fill="black") + scale_x_continuous("Year") + scale_y_discrete("# of New Programs") + scale_shape_manual("", values = c(6,5)) + theme_bw()

Unfortunately, this model is not great. It does predict some years perfectly (for example, 1975 and 1976), though for many other years it over predicts the number of new programs. Also, to get these results we had to set the prediction threshold to be very low.
